        "excerpt": "After Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon had carried away captive Jeconiah the son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah… the LORD showed me.",
        "body": "The chapter's first verse is its most precise historical marker, and its precision is theologically intentional. Jeconiah (also called Jehoiachin or Coniah) was deported in the spring of 597 BC along with his mother, court officials, craftsmen, and smiths — a number Jeremiah 52:28 specifies as 3,023 persons. The deportation had three effects: it stripped Judah of its skilled class, it placed a puppet (Zedekiah) on the throne under Babylonian supervision, and it created two competing communities — exiles in Babylon and survivors in Jerusalem — each with rival theological claims about God's favor.\n\nThe Babylonian survivors' argument ran as follows: we have the land, the temple, and the Davidic seat. The exiles are gone. We are the preserved remnant. Therefore, God is with us. This argument was not fringe — it was culturally dominant (Ezek. 11:15 gives the same logic verbatim: 'Keep far from the LORD; this land has been given us as a possession'). It was also the position that made Jeremiah's ministry most dangerous, because Jeremiah had consistently called for submission to Babylon, a posture that looked like treason and apostasy from within the Jerusalem perspective.\n\nInto this competing-claims context, the LORD shows Jeremiah a vision — not a public proclamation but a private prophetic revelation ('the LORD showed me,' v.1). The vision is placed before the temple of the LORD (v.1), God's own house, the very locus of Jerusalem's claim to divine presence. The location is deliberate: the verdict is issued from the place that the surviving Judahites are using as their evidence of God's favor. The temple itself becomes the site of their exposure.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Galah* (to carry away captive, v.1) is the exile-verb par excellence in the Hebrew prophets, used for the Assyrian deportation of the north (2 Kings 17:6) and now for Judah. *Hekhal* (temple, v.1) is the inner sanctuary — not the outer courts but God's dwelling-place specifically. The vision is positioned at the most sacred spot in Israel's geography."
