        "excerpt": "Then the LORD said to me, 'What do you see, Jeremiah?' And I said, 'Figs, the good figs, very good; and the bad figs, very bad, which cannot be eaten due to rottenness.'",
        "body": "The structure of the prophetic vision in Jeremiah 24 follows a pattern well-established in the Hebrew prophets: visual datum presented → divine question posed → prophet answers → divine interpretation given. The same sequence appears in Amos 7:7-8 (the plumb line), Amos 8:1-2 (the basket of summer fruit), and Zechariah 4:2 (the golden lampstand). The function of the divine question — 'What do you see?' — is not informational. God does not need Jeremiah's answer. The question disciplines the prophet to articulate what he has observed before receiving its meaning. It models the inductive discipline that sound biblical study requires: description before interpretation.\n\nJeremiah's answer in verse 3 repeats the quality-contrast four times: good figs, very good; bad figs, very bad, which cannot be eaten. The repetition mirrors the structure of the vision itself — two baskets, absolute poles, no middle ground. The Hebrew text piles up the vocabulary of goodness (*tov, meod*) and badness (*ra, roa*) to establish that the quality difference is total and unambiguous. There is no third basket of mediocre figs. There is no mixed category. The vision's binary structure is the theological point before any interpretation is given: God's evaluative categories are not a spectrum.\n\nThe transition in verse 4 — 'Then the word of the LORD came to me, saying' — marks the shift from vision to oracle. The vision provides the image; the oracle provides the meaning. This two-stage structure protects the interpretation from being arbitrary: the image is fixed, and the meaning is given, not inferred by the prophet. The authority of the oracle derives from its divine source, not from Jeremiah's interpretive skill.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davar Yehovah* (the word of the LORD, v.4) is Jeremiah's standard formula for prophetic oracle — appearing over 150 times in the book. Its use here signals that what follows is not prophetic meditation but direct divine speech. *Teenah* (fig) was a first-fruits crop — the early fig (*bikkurah*) was the sweetest and most prized, making the comparison in 24:2 precise: the exiles are not merely good but premier, first-quality."
